WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.420
 - Hello, and welcome to our lecture on AJAX and JSON.

00:00:02.420 --> 00:00:04.260
 I'm Dr. Earl Severance, and I'm your professor,

00:00:04.260 --> 00:00:07.020
 and I just wanna, I got a nice Father's Day gift

00:00:07.020 --> 00:00:10.920
 from my daughter, and so I'm, to thank her,

00:00:10.920 --> 00:00:13.300
 I'm wearing it for this particular lecture.

00:00:13.300 --> 00:00:17.160
 So, we have been doing a whole bunch of stuff

00:00:17.160 --> 00:00:19.120
 with the request-response cycle, right?

00:00:19.120 --> 00:00:23.120
 We go in the server, we run through URLs,

00:00:23.120 --> 00:00:27.320
 we enter views, we write templates, we send HTML back,

00:00:27.320 --> 00:00:30.020
 and the browser parses that response

00:00:30.020 --> 00:00:33.200
 and puts it in the document object model,

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:35.820
 and then most of what we've done has been just sort of fiddling

00:00:35.820 --> 00:00:38.000
 with the document object model with JavaScript,

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:41.620
 but now we're going to take another important step,

00:00:41.620 --> 00:00:44.200
 and that is, we're going to do things

00:00:44.200 --> 00:00:45.620
 in the document object model,

00:00:45.620 --> 00:00:47.600
 and to the document object model,

00:00:47.600 --> 00:00:51.620
 where the JavaScript itself is going to make requests

00:00:51.620 --> 00:00:54.500
 to our server code, gonna run through the views,

00:00:54.500 --> 00:00:57.360
 run through the URLs, and send data back.

00:00:57.360 --> 00:01:00.020
 So the difference is, we're not just sending markup back,

00:01:00.020 --> 00:01:02.060
 HTML is our markup format,

00:01:02.060 --> 00:01:06.860
 and JSON is our data format.

00:01:06.860 --> 00:01:09.560
 So, the web is pretty old now.

00:01:09.560 --> 00:01:11.700
 We started on 2003,

00:01:11.700 --> 00:01:15.960
 and the request-response cycle was pretty cool,

00:01:15.960 --> 00:01:18.200
 and lots of software, lots of libraries,

00:01:18.200 --> 00:01:21.800
 lots of languages knew how to talk back and forth

00:01:21.800 --> 00:01:24.100
 across the internet and get data,

00:01:24.100 --> 00:01:27.700
 and the question was, is why don't we get something

00:01:27.700 --> 00:01:31.160
 other than HTML, and then the argument became

00:01:31.160 --> 00:01:33.700
 what was the syntax that we should use,

00:01:33.700 --> 00:01:36.200
 and you can look at my shirt here, somewhere here,

00:01:36.200 --> 00:01:38.860
 right there's my shirt, you got some curly braces,

00:01:38.860 --> 00:01:40.500
 and then you got some slashes,

00:01:40.500 --> 00:01:43.200
 and that actually turned out to be the argument.

00:01:43.200 --> 00:01:47.300
 The argument was whether or not you would use XML, right?

00:01:47.300 --> 00:01:49.260
 Whether you use XML or curly braces.

00:01:49.260 --> 00:01:51.920
 Now, XML was the first thing,

00:01:51.920 --> 00:01:55.960
 and if we hear the word Ajax, that x stands for XML,

00:01:55.960 --> 00:01:59.920
 but most of the time we are not sending XML back and forth,

00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:02.560
 we're sending JSON back and forth.

00:02:02.560 --> 00:02:06.400
 So the idea of moving data across the network,

00:02:06.400 --> 00:02:09.660
 we had to agree on what's called a wire format,

00:02:09.660 --> 00:02:11.920
 or you could think of it as the network,

00:02:11.920 --> 00:02:14.560
 as if we're watching it on a wire and it's going by,

00:02:14.560 --> 00:02:16.020
 what would we actually send?

00:02:16.020 --> 00:02:18.760
 'Cause in PHP we have arrays,

00:02:18.760 --> 00:02:19.960
 in Python we have dictionaries,

00:02:19.960 --> 00:02:22.360
 in JavaScript we have objects, and Java has things

00:02:22.360 --> 00:02:24.700
 like hash maps and array lists.

00:02:24.700 --> 00:02:27.020
 And the question is, what are we gonna send back and forth?

00:02:27.020 --> 00:02:29.860
 We gotta agree on it, so that we can write something

00:02:29.860 --> 00:02:31.460
 in Python and read it in JavaScript,

00:02:31.460 --> 00:02:33.420
 and similarly write it in PHP,

00:02:33.420 --> 00:02:34.560
 and then read it in JavaScript,

00:02:34.560 --> 00:02:37.760
 so we have to agree on a wire format.

00:02:37.760 --> 00:02:40.720
 And XML is one of the wire formats,

00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:41.620
 we're not gonna talk about it,

00:02:41.620 --> 00:02:44.960
 'cause that argument is kinda over.

00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:48.360
 XML is not bad for documents at rest,

00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:51.360
 but it's not a real good wire format.

00:02:51.360 --> 00:02:54.200
 So we'll just pretend that JSON is the wire format,

00:02:54.200 --> 00:02:56.960
 even though it is a wire format.

00:02:56.960 --> 00:03:00.500
 The idea is, is that we have to take a structure

00:03:00.500 --> 00:03:03.960
 that's inside a server, and we have to serialize it,

00:03:03.960 --> 00:03:05.760
 which means convert it to a string.

00:03:05.760 --> 00:03:07.020
 So it's a Python dictionary,

00:03:07.020 --> 00:03:10.120
 which is object-oriented mechanisms

00:03:10.120 --> 00:03:11.560
 that make all this stuff work.

00:03:11.560 --> 00:03:15.160
 And then we have to say, oh, let's turn this into a string,

00:03:15.160 --> 00:03:17.360
 'cause we have to send characters across the internet,

00:03:17.360 --> 00:03:19.300
 and then when we receive it on the far end,

00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:20.760
 we do what's called deserialize,

00:03:20.760 --> 00:03:22.520
 and the word serial means

00:03:22.520 --> 00:03:24.420
 that we're sending it kinda one character at a time,

00:03:24.420 --> 00:03:26.800
 back in the old days when we used modems,

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:28.920
 and leased lines, and things like that,

00:03:28.920 --> 00:03:31.920
 though see my internet history for some of that.

00:03:31.920 --> 00:03:32.920
 So we deserialize it,

00:03:32.920 --> 00:03:35.420
 and it becomes sort of an object in JavaScript,

00:03:35.420 --> 00:03:37.560
 in this case, if we're going from Python to JavaScript.

00:03:37.560 --> 00:03:39.960
 But the idea is that the wire format

00:03:39.960 --> 00:03:42.060
 is something we agree on,

00:03:42.060 --> 00:03:44.500
 and so it doesn't matter what language we're dealing with,

00:03:44.500 --> 00:03:46.360
 the wire format is something each language

00:03:46.360 --> 00:03:48.260
 has to be able to serialize, to send,

00:03:48.260 --> 00:03:51.320
 and deserialize to receive.

00:03:51.320 --> 00:03:53.820
 So I have a video, an interview that I did a long time ago

00:03:53.820 --> 00:03:55.460
 with a fellow named Douglas Cockford,

00:03:55.460 --> 00:03:58.660
 he does not claim he's the inventor of JSON,

00:03:58.660 --> 00:04:00.420
 he's just the person who said,

00:04:00.420 --> 00:04:04.020
 wow, this is a really cool format, and let's write it down.

00:04:04.020 --> 00:04:07.900
 And it's really nothing more than a slight adjustment

00:04:07.900 --> 00:04:11.200
 to the object literal notation, meaning the constant,

00:04:11.200 --> 00:04:13.620
 what a constant is in JavaScript

00:04:13.620 --> 00:04:15.860
 when you wanna just assign a constant.

00:04:15.860 --> 00:04:18.400
 So we say X equals two, two's that constant,

00:04:18.400 --> 00:04:21.900
 but you can also say X equals curly brace something.

00:04:21.900 --> 00:04:26.120
 And so he's like, well, why don't we just use this?

00:04:26.120 --> 00:04:30.160
 And he called it JSON, and he registered JSON.org,

00:04:30.160 --> 00:04:33.820
 and it just turns out, I really wish I knew

00:04:33.820 --> 00:04:38.820
 the extent to which imitating the Python dictionary syntax

00:04:38.820 --> 00:04:40.520
 was part of the goal.

00:04:40.520 --> 00:04:42.360
 In some ways, it's almost more similar

00:04:42.360 --> 00:04:48.480
 to Python dictionary syntax when you're doing key value pairs, when the keys are strings

00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:56.080
 in Python dictionary. So this is some legitimate JavaScript code. This is a constant. I could

00:04:56.080 --> 00:05:01.800
 say who equals X or I could see who equals open curly brace, name colon Chuck, age colon

00:05:01.800 --> 00:05:06.520
 29, college colon true, you know, strings, integers, Booleans, you can have lists and

00:05:06.520 --> 00:05:10.600
 you can have objects within objects and lists within objects and blah blah blah blah blah

00:05:10.600 --> 00:05:16.960
 blah. So it's a pretty simple syntax. I mean, part of the thing that Crockford argues is

00:05:16.960 --> 00:05:22.480
 that it's just a syntax that any developer, if left alone long enough, would just invent

00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:28.240
 it. And I have to agree with that. I have to say that this syntax, I can't say, whoa,

00:05:28.240 --> 00:05:35.560
 I don't like this. I wish I could improve on it somehow. So the JSON syntax is not exactly

00:05:35.560 --> 00:05:40.240
 the same as the JavaScript syntax. It's kind of like, let's keep it simple and have a subset

00:05:40.240 --> 00:05:45.760
 of the JavaScript object literal syntax. And so I've got a sample, some sample code that

00:05:45.760 --> 00:05:50.520
 you can go play with. And all it does is it says who equals open curly brace, blah blah

00:05:50.520 --> 00:05:53.920
 blah, blah, blah, exactly the code I showed you before and console dot log it. That's

00:05:53.920 --> 00:05:57.640
 all it does. It doesn't print it. It doesn't send it across the network. It doesn't do

00:05:57.640 --> 00:06:03.200
 anything. It just console dot logs it. And you see that that is the way we define a constant

00:06:03.200 --> 00:06:11.160
 object. An object is a constant. But that's not so interesting. What is more interesting

00:06:11.160 --> 00:06:17.440
 is when we can produce code inside of the server in, say, Python and then send it to

00:06:17.440 --> 00:06:23.920
 a browser. So here we have a very simple view. And the sample code is up there on DJ4E.com

00:06:23.920 --> 00:06:32.800
 for you to look at. And we are going to have a JSON fun path. This is going to be a function

00:06:32.800 --> 00:06:38.440
 style view. Time sleep is just so that when you play with a sample, it pauses for just

00:06:38.440 --> 00:06:43.880
 a moment. Normally you wouldn't pause. So we just construct a dictionary. That's a Python

00:06:43.880 --> 00:06:49.080
 dictionary. And again, wow. It looks a lot like a JavaScript object. But if you do it

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:52.280
 in PHP, it looks quite different. If you do it in Java, it looks quite different. But

00:06:52.280 --> 00:06:56.840
 it turns out in Python and JavaScript, they're very similar. And then we're returning JSON

00:06:56.840 --> 00:07:05.320
 response and then handing that dictionary. Now normally when we have a normal HTML page,

00:07:05.320 --> 00:07:10.120
 we're sending back an HTTP response. And we're sending a string back. But this time we're

00:07:10.120 --> 00:07:15.600
 sending a JSON response. And we're sending an object back. Django sees JSON response

00:07:15.600 --> 00:07:18.840
 and says, I'm going to set the headers the right way. I'm going to serialize this. And

00:07:18.840 --> 00:07:26.320
 I'm going to send this thing out as a string. And so if you go to this endpoint, JSON fun,

00:07:26.320 --> 00:07:31.840
 when you look at it in raw data, you see that it's been compressed into a string. That's

00:07:31.840 --> 00:07:37.160
 really curly brace, double quote, yada yada. Now you also see your browser sometimes shows

00:07:37.160 --> 00:07:43.560
 it parsed, meaning it's showing it after parsing. So you can see the raw data before parsing.

00:07:43.560 --> 00:07:48.680
 And then you can actually see the JSON data after parsing. It's kind of the same thing.

00:07:48.680 --> 00:07:55.880
 It's just one's a string and one is an object. And part and parcel of moving JSON back and

00:07:55.880 --> 00:08:00.240
 forth to the browser is you got things like the content type, which is application slash

00:08:00.240 --> 00:08:06.560
 JSON rather than text slash HTML. And then there's other things like content size, et

00:08:06.560 --> 00:08:13.120
 cetera, et cetera, et cetera. So that's about all there is to JSON. It's so simple. It's

00:08:13.120 --> 00:08:18.060
 so elegant. So up next, we're going to talk about doing a chat app, which really brings

00:08:18.060 --> 00:08:29.680
 together a lot of this JavaScript, JavaScript objects, JavaScript in the browser and JSON.

